        <h1>Electrical Safety Tips for Your Home</h1>
        <p>Protect your family and property by following these simple guidelines.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <article class="blog-post">
      <div class="container">
        <p>Electricity makes modern life possible, but the systems behind your walls need respect and maintenance. Safety starts with recognizing small warning signs and addressing them before they become hazards. Below is a practical checklist you can use at home, along with guidance on when to call an electrician.</p>
        <h2>Know the Warning Signs</h2>
        <p>Electrical issues usually start small. If you notice any of the following, it's time to investigate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Flickering or dimming lights when appliances turn on.</li>
          <li>Outlets or switches that are warm to the touch.</li>
          <li>Breakers that trip frequently or won't reset.</li>
          <li>Buzzing sounds from fixtures, switches, or the panel.</li>
          <li>Burning odors near outlets or the electrical panel.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>These symptoms can signal loose connections, overloaded circuits, or aging equipment. If you're unsure, start with professional troubleshooting. The <a href="/electrical-repairs">electrical repairs &amp; troubleshooting service</a> page explains what that process looks like.</p>
        <h2>Don't Overload Circuits</h2>
        <p>Plugging multiple high-demand appliances into the same circuit can overheat wiring and trip breakers. Spread loads across different outlets and avoid daisy-chaining power strips. If your home runs out of circuit capacity, it may be time to evaluate the panel and overall service. The <a href="/panel-upgrades">panel upgrade page</a> covers signs that an upgrade may be needed.</p>
        <h2>Use GFCI Protection Near Water</h2>
        <p>Ground-fault circuit interrupter (GFCI) outlets shut off power when they detect a fault. They are designed for areas where water and electricity can mix, such as bathrooms, kitchens, laundry rooms, garages, and outdoor outlets. If you're not sure whether your outlets are protected, an electrician can test and confirm.</p>
        <h2>Inspect Cords and Plugs</h2>
        <p>Damaged cords are a common source of electrical hazards. Replace cords that are frayed, cracked, or feel hot. Avoid running extension cords under rugs or furniture, where heat can build up. Use the correct gauge and length for the tool or appliance you're powering.</p>
        <h2>Be Cautious with Space Heaters and Portable Devices</h2>
        <p>Space heaters and portable AC units draw significant power. Plug them directly into a wall outlet, not into a power strip. Give them space to breathe and keep them away from curtains, bedding, and flammable materials.</p>
        <h2>Check for Loose or Aging Devices</h2>
        <p>Outlets and switches wear out over time, especially in high-use areas. If a plug feels loose, the connection can arc and generate heat. If a switch crackles or feels hot, it's time to replace it. These are small fixes, but they have a big impact on safety.</p>
        <h2>Understand Your Electrical Panel</h2>
        <p>Know where your panel is located and which circuits control major parts of the house. If you see rust, scorch marks, or a strong odor near the panel, shut off the affected circuit and call for service. Avoid repeated breaker resets without diagnosis—breakers trip for a reason.</p>
        <h2>Plan for Safety During Renovations</h2>
        <p>Remodels and additions often add lighting, outlets, or new appliances. Before starting, verify your panel has enough capacity and space for new circuits. A good plan avoids overloading and reduces the need for last-minute changes.</p>
        <h2>When to Call a Professional</h2>
        <p>If you encounter sparks, burning smells, or any sign of overheating, shut off the circuit if it's safe to do so and call an electrician. Electrical work is not a DIY category—proper testing and safe connections protect your home and family.</p>
